SIMPLE: oligomer
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: oligomer
<hw>o*lig"o*mer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>
<def>A molecule composed of a small number of linked monomer units; a
short polymer; -- compounds called <ex>oligomers</ex> have less than one
hundred monomer units and usually less than thirty. Oligomers of
increasing length are called <stype>dimer</stype>,
<stype>trimer</stype>, <stype>tetramer</stype>, <stype>pentamer</stype>,
<stype>hexamer</stype>, <stype>heptamer</stype>, <stype>octamer</stype>,
<stype>nonamer</stype>, <stype>decamer</stype>, etc. In colloquial
laboratory jargon, they may also be referred to as
<stype>nine-mer</stype>, <stype>ten-mer</stype>,
<stype>eleven-mer</stype>, <stype>twelve-mer</stype>, etc., especially
for oligomers of greater than eight units.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oligomerous</ent>⟦br⟧
